<response>None<//response>< review>
I just moved downtown a few months ago and ending up stumbling upon this cute little Italian restaurant called Toscana right in the heart of the Gaslamp. A friendly hostess named Caitlin greeted me and sat me at a nice table on their patio‚Äì it‚Äôs the perfect place to people watch. My server was AJ and he was incredibly friendly! He recommended that I order a drink from their espresso bar and I‚Äôm very glad he did! Coffee is the best I‚Äôve had downtown. I ended up ordering the special of the day which was a steak and spring mix salad! I don‚Äôt eat steak much but it was to die for! It was like butter‚Äì it melted in your mouth! <Review>Recently moved to the area and needed a new groomer for my dog. Although there are a good amount of 1 star ratings I thought I would give them a try since their overall was a 4.0 rating and to be honest there are not a lot of small business groomers in the area. The people were very friendly and the groomer asked and listened to what kind of cut I wanted. When I picked up my dog she had one of the worst haircuts I've ever seen her get (and there was only one other time I felt this way about a cut my dog got). I‚Äôm not picky at all and usually don‚Äôt mind a little bit of choppiness cause it just grows back..Her body looked uneven which was pretty bad, but I could see past, but her face was SO CHOPPY. I had to use my husband's clippers to try my best to fix it. It was that bad that I felt the need to fix it immediately when we got home. Her cut was nothing like her head shape too! She looked like a different dog. They cut it short down the center of her face then longer around the sides like she had a middle part. Her ears weren't even trimmed..I'm not sure if I got someone new. I love supporting small grooming businesses and the people were very friendly, but for the price (which was a bit higher where I usually go to) I don't plan to ever go back. I really contemplated calling to bring my dog back to have them try to fix it, but decided I didn't want to risk her coming back worse. I want to add that my dog gets tons of cuts (every 3 months) so I know she is good when she gets groomed so I'm not sure how she messed up so badly :/ she is a Pomeranian poodle mix, but her hair is like a Pomeranian. Lastly, I dropped my dog off at 12 noon and they told me she would be done at 4pm which is long for a cut. Places like petco take 4 hours and I know they leave dogs in crates, which is why I only go to smaller grooming businesses that usually only take 2-2.5hours so I was already hesitant. After 4 hours I don‚Äôt receive any call that she's done and the store was closing in an hour. Someone else brought my dog out..I usually never write reviews unless a place is outstanding because great businesses deserve great reviews or unless my experience is horrible enough for me to want to warn future customers. < UserId.>
108308844176220134171< /UserId.>
<Name>Thad King<//Name>< date>
1523904432190< /date>
<Rate>5<//Rate>< Review>
Have you every watched the Rose Parade on New Years morning.  Well the Tournament house is where the parade begins. The Tournament House offers free guided tours every Thursday at 2 pm and 3 pm.  The tour leaders are well versed in the history of the Rose Parade and Rose Bowl.  They also share some very interesting and humorous stories about past parades and games.  The Tournament House was formerly owned by William Wrigley and his wife.  The Tournament House is also known as the Wrigley Mansion.  Your tour starts with a video history and proceeds up to the second floor.  The tour takes you into the Queen and Princesses suite and then descends to the first floor living room, dining room and entry hall.  The entry hall has a pipe organ that is still operable.  This is a hidden gem in Pasadena and a must see.< /Review>

<Text>Yes, it seems very pricey; however, the experience is unbelievable. The excitement that I could never get from watching TV. Definitely want to do this once in my life time.

Parade starts at 8am; they suggest you arrive by 6am. Finding parking structures can be challenging since many streets are blocked. Wear comfortable shoes, because lots of walking!!

It is very cold in the morning, wear layers!! They allow food/drinks, just not bottles. There are security check points. There provide portable restrooms too.

Overall, fantastic experience!!!<//Text><gmapID>0x80c2c382a53a1c99:0x9d3a194b00cc237e</gmapID><user_id>112509210362668820607<//user_id><pics>None</pics><Time>1531456935677<//Time>< name>

OMG you HAVE to see the parade in person!  The floats are so much grander than on TV, and you don't have to listen to the commentary!  Be sure you also take the building tour.  It is amazing to see the detail involved in building these beautiful things.  The horsemanship in the parade is also amazing.  You miss a lot of their tricks on TV.  The bands are also very good.  Many of them dance and do  aerobatics while marching/playing that isn't caught on camera.<//Text>

<user>103053669044093866694<//user>< name>
Raquel Hunter</name>
< review>
I have taken FREE tours of the Tournament House every summer since moving to Pasadena and each time, I learn something different. When you take a tour, you'll watch a quick video, and then be lead by a volunteer through almost all of the rooms in the house. It is really amazing to see construction and features of this old home.

The Tournament House, located what was known in the early 1900s as Millionaire Row is the official headquarters of the Pasadena Tournament of Roses Association. It has some paid staff, but is largely operated by volunteers.

Chewing gum magnate William Wrigley Jr. purchased the home in 1914 for $170,000. It was one of their vacation homes.</review>

< user_id>
103770800223142180595< /user_id>
< username>
Richard L< /username>
<date>1418864605684</date><rate>5<//rate>< text>
@~)~~~~       @~)~~~~         @~)~~~~       @~)~~~~

I decide to pick Rose Parade.  It is my first time attending this very popular event, living here so long yet it is my first time.  This year rose parade is the 125th anniversary. It has a lot of variety of float from local city, Nonprofit, University, to Private Corporation.

One of my concern is the parking, surprise it was not really an issue.  Our group didn't get there until after 7am,  we were able to find a good parking spot about 3 blocks away which is about five minutes' walk.  It was a lot easier compare to the site when they park their float after the parade.  Which is far harder to finding street and they charge money for nearby parking and admission.  While the parade is, free!

Even though we only got here one hour prior the parade, it was not too hard to find a good spot to see the parade.  Advice brings a [portable folding chair.  Don't bother bring a mat is quite dirty in the street thanks to many camper who often do not take care of their own mess.  Make sure bring a camera and a tripod if you really into photography.  Camcorder would also be handy.

This year float was overall average; the only stand out float that I was impress is the Honda one.  Huge bullet train alike got a giant camera too.  The one thing you do not see in close up float is that there is marching band and of course, the military planes fly-by. I wish they would add some speaker or a least an apps that allow you to hear the live coverage so you would get to know the history of the float while it passed by.  There is one thing you do not see in the TV is the army of cleanup crews after each group of horses pass by. Some of the float equip with music was a nice touch.  The reality show Voice also got a voice, which was a surprise.  There was several winner singers present in the float but none of the judge. Vin Scully the voice of Dodgers was this year Grand Marshal.

Overall, I do think it was worth my time and was long overdue seeing the rose parade.  It was not as crowded and actually pretty well organized in most part.  I think the grand park downtown countdown has something to do with reduce crowd.  Anyway, this is a one thing you must do to when you visit or live in L.A. or in SoCal.  It is only kind in the world in this scale.   @~)~~~~< /text>

<user_id>115728374842901942835<//user_id><name>Veronica Rodriguez<//name>< time>
1582955858993</time>
< Rating>
5</Rating>
< Text>
Finally a great mexican restaurant in Chino. The restaurant was packed on a Friday night @ 9 pm. The hostess and waiter were super friendly and customer service oriented. Chips came out hot and crunchy, and salsa was good. At our table we ordered a grilled shrimp burrito, carne en su jugo, and a mango cart on tap beer.I am not often impressed with mexican food, as many times it is not flavorful.  What a surprise. The burrito was amazing, just tasty and bursting with flavor and spices. The grilled peppers and shrimp were grilled to perfection. The carne en su jugo was extremely flavorful. Meat was tender. This is definitely a go to place for a great tasting mexican meal.</Text>

<Date>1592810117347< /Date><Rate>5<//Rate>< review>
This place has seriously good Mexican food. 2 dishes in particular are worth the visit - Carne en su jugo & Casa grande burrito. The Carne is an absolutely delectable beef stew absolutely brimming with flavor and hearty goodness. This is one of the best Mexican dishes north of border made in a restaurant. The burrito is also no joke, they pack it with your choice of 3 meats and chipotle flavor and it is HUGE. If you‚Äôre someone who likes big burritos, I can confidently say you don‚Äôt know what you‚Äôre talking about until you‚Äôve had this one. It needs its own special extra long to-go container and can easily be split by two hungry guys. Everything else is standard fare but quite well done. This place deserves a visit.</review>

< review>
DIAKADI is a true gem in SF. I'm the type of person who's always thought "I don't need a trainer, I know how to lift weights". I bet many of you reading this might feel the same way. Let me tell you - it's worth it. I learned SO MUCH and had a great time in the process. Switch your mindset a little bit, and think of it as an education as well as fitness. Or an investment in your health. You'll learn SO MUCH about how to train your body safely. As someone who's struggled with lower back pain for years, this was really helpful for me.

The trainers at DIAKADI are absolutely spectacular, and they've each been vetted by an extremely professional and experienced staff. I worked with Kelly and would highly recommend her. Anyone who' has made the cut to become a trainer at DIAKADI is worth your time. Each trainer has their unique focus and experience and DIAKADI is wonderful about matching you up with someone who fits your specific needs. This is not a "one size fits all" training gym.

In the time of COVID, this place has also gone above and beyond to create a safe space for fitness. Honestly, right now is a great time to focus on health.

Simply put, there's a reason that this facility is so respected in the fitness community. If you care about your health and you value functional strength and fitness, then this is your place to make it happen.<//review>

<name>Austin Villamil< /name><Date>1605742770320<//Date><Rate>5</Rate>< Text>
Diakadi is an incredible place because of the beautiful facility, master practitioners, dedicated staff and leadership from its owners.

The gym has a complete arsenal of equipment, tools and resources so that any client has what he or she needs to execute workouts, receive therapy and achieve goals. From private treatment rooms to olympic platforms and traditional strength training equipment to athletic turfs, Diakadi hands down has the best personal training facility in the Bay Area that is even superior to most commercial gyms.

There is a diverse selection of coaches and therapists who are all extremely passionate about their craft and who make up Diakadi's community. Each practitioner pursues education and mastery in whatever niche they gravitate towards and this ensures that no matter what your goals are, there is someone who is the perfect match to guide you on your health and fitness journey.

As a facility, Diakadi is run extremely smoothly and professionally and this has not changed one bit due to Covid. The expert staff have adapted so that there is temperature check upon entry, requirement to wear a mask at all times, reserved session slots to prevent overcrowding, spacing between practitioners and clients and other sessions around them, tools for cleaning and disinfecting, mandatory cleaning periods and the list goes on. They have seamlessly made this version of training in the gym the new normal, and all without losing the warm and welcoming atmosphere that makes Diakadi what it is.

Finally, none of this would be possible if it wasn't for the direction from Billy and Mike, the owners of Diakadi. Billy and Mike are the masterminds who, over the years, built Diakadi from the ground up, designing this beautiful and complete space and gathering intelligent and passionate individuals who make up their staff and practitioners. But all of this is just as impressive as their perseverance and leadership during these hard and trying Covid times. While most small businesses in San Francisco and around the country fought and still fight to stay open, Billy and Mike unified training studios in the city through the San Francisco Independent Fitness Studio Coalition (SFIFSC), their organization to help gyms rise up together and prove that it is indeed possible to keep gyms safe so that people can prioritize their health and fitness. When they were struggling to keep their own business afloat they didn't just look out for themselves - they decided to help save San Francisco's entire personal training industry.

If you are looking for a place to begin working towards your health, fitness and life goals surrounded by a community that is knowledgable, experienced and driven, then look no further. It is an honor and privilege to be a personal trainer and bodyworker here at Diakadi.</Text>
